{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/00514154442/1949021801/0297.xml":{"full_text":"THE DAILY ALASKA EMPIRE\n\u201cALL THE NEWS ALL THE TIME\u2019\nVOL. LXXII., NO. 11,123\nJUNEAU, ALASKA, FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 18, 1949\nMEMBER ASSOCIATED PRESS\nPRICE TEN CENTS\nPROPERTY TAX\nBILL WOULD\nDOUBLE TAX\nFOR SCHOOLS\n$10.50 Proposal Reap\npears-National Guard\nAd Is Debated\nBy JIM HUTCHESON\nA proposal to increase the terri\ntory\u2019s school tax from $5 to $10.50\nper person came back to the House\nyesterday afternoon.\nA similar measure passed the\nHouse during the special session but\ndied in the Senate. It was reintro-\nduced by Rep. Warren Taylor. Fair-\nbanks Democrat. It provides that\n44 per cent of the receipts would\ngo to the \u201cUniversities of Al&ska\"\nfor salaries and 56 per cent to pub\nlic school salaries.\nIt was one of three bills intro- j\nduced during the afternoon. Two\nmemorials also appeared.\nThe House passed two bills dur-\ning the afternoon and completed\nthe nearly two hours of reading the j\nbulky bill for creation of the pro-\nposed Alaska National Guard, with 1\nseveral amendments being made.\nThe bills passed provide $2,500 ex- I\ntrr compensation for the Attorney j\nGeneral for his special services for j\nthe legislature and would forbid\nstanding passengers in buses on\ntrips more than 15 miles from an\nAlaska city center. The attorney\ngeneral compensation bill passed 14\nto 9 after prolonged wrangling. It\noriginally had proposed $1,000. That i\nwas cut to $500 Wednesday. On re\nconsideration yesterday an amend- j\nment was offered to put it back\nto $1,000, but Rep. Glen Franklin,\na supporter of the $500 figure,!\ncounter-proposed $2,500 when it\nlooked as though the $1,000 would\nbe approved. The House voted for\nthe $2,500 amendment. Franklin was\naccused of trying to kill the bill by j\nmaking it too high. As expected\nby virtually everyone in the House\nchamber, Franklin then voted 1\nagcinst the bill in final form.\nThe vote by which Rep. Frank\nAngerman's no-standing bus bill\npassed was 16 to 8.\nBus Bill Exemption\nThe stiffest provisions were cut\nfrom the bill. j\nAs finally passed, the bill says\nbus passengers don\u2019t have to be\nseated on trips within 15 miles of a\ncity center. Franklin moved for\nthe amendment to replace a 10-mile\namendment, arguing Juneau had a I\nlocal bus running 14 miles out.\nAngerman .objected vigorously to i\nstretching the exemption. The bill j\nalso exempts buses now in Alaska j\n(Continued on Page 2)\nThe Washington!\nMerry-Go-Round\nBy DREW PEARSON\n(Copyrltht, 1949. by Bell Syndicste. Inc.) j\nWashington\u2014it was kept very\nhush-hush, but Norwegian Foreign j\nMinister Halvard Lange had a very\nsignificant secret luncheon with a\ngroup of Congressional leaders in\nHouse Speaker Sam Rayburn's off\nice just before he returned to Oslo.\nAt the luncheon, the Norwegian\ndiplomat shrewdly let his hair\ndown to tell American Congress\nional leaders his nation's troubles\nresulting from its willingness to I\njoin the dynamite-laden Atlantic\nDefense Pact. Norway has been un\nder terrific pressure from the Rus-\nsians not to join with the West- j\nern powers In a mutual-defense\naf reement.\nLange told the Congressmen who\nmet him that Norway was not wor\nried about whether or not to throw\nin its lot with the West. Rather,\nLange said, the thing that concern\ned the Norwegians, as well as the\nDanes, was what would happen in\nthe event Russia began massing\ntroops near the Norwegian border\nduring the period while Congress\ndebated and before American aid\nbecame effective. Lange showed a\nbrilliant knowledge of the Ameri\ncan legislative process.\nHe estimated it might be five\nmonths before American aid reach\neo Norway in quantity. It was\nthis lag, the Foreign Minister said,\nthat was causing the Norwegians\nso much conctrh.\nHouse Speaker Sam Ttayburn and\n(Continued on Page Four)\nHooper Bay\nGets Food\nBy Airlift\nANCHORAGE, Feb. 18.\u2014Wt\u2014 A\nJato-equipped C-47 plane of the\nICth Rescue Squadron is scheduled\nto leave Elmendorf Field .today with\n4,450 pounds of emergency food for\nvillagers at Hooper Bay on the Ber\ning Sea Coast.\nThe Alaska Native Service receiv\ned the request from the cooperative\nstore there, saying the 290 villagers\nwere short on staples. The A.N.S.\nboug.it the food from the Army and\nthe Alaskan Air Command volun\nteered to fly it to the village.\nFr ezing rain conditions at Hoop\ner Bay kept the plane from making\nthe trip yesterday afternoon.\nThe plane will carry 20 cases of\nmilk, 40 bags* of flour, 10 sacks ot\nsugar, 10 cases of coffee and 5C\npounds of tea.\nThe ski-equipped plane plans to\nland on a frozen lagoon if conditions\npermit, otherwise it will make a\nparachute drop from low altitude.\nThe villagers did not have suffi\ncient money to order enough staples\nlast spring in order for it to be\nplaced aboard ship. Now the villag\ners have the money, the food must\nbe flown to them, an official ex\nplained.\nHe said the villagers were not in\nany danger but the food was being\nsent to supplement the native diet.'\n4 GENERALS\nREASSIGNED;\nHITS ALASKA\nj _____\nj WASHINGTON, Feb. 18.\u2014\u2014\nThe Air Force announces reassign\nment of four generals.\nBrig. Gen. Donald R. Hutchinson,\ncommanding general of the 307th\n|Bomb Wing, MacDill Air Force base,\nat Tampa. Fla., will become com\njmanding general of the 5020th wing.\n'Davis Air Force base, Adak, Aleu\ntian Islands.\nMaj. General Joseph H. Atkinson\ni commanding general of the Alaskan\nAir Command, Fort Richardson, Al\naska, has been named commanding\n'general of the 311th Air Division,\nI reconnaissance, Topeka Air Force\nbase, Kansas.\nj Brig. G^n. Paul T. Cullen, now\ncommanding the 311th Air Division,\nwill become deputy to Atkinson.\nBrig. Gen. Frank A. Armstrong,\nJr., chief of staff of the Alaskan\nAir Command, will replace Atkin\nson as commanding general of the\nAAC.\nSWITCHMAN FOR\ni A. R.R. IS KILLED\nBY LOCOMOTIVE\nANCHORAGE, Feb. 18.\u2014(AP>\u2014His\nhead covered by a heavy parka and\nwith a nearby machine shop making\na lot of noise, Columbus Jones, 42\nyear-old Negro Alaska Railroad\nswitchman, did not hear a backina\nlocomotive at the freight terminal\nyards.\nHe was killed almost instantly.\nRailroad officials said they plan\nned a full investigation.\nHis next of kin was listed as Mrs.\nj Maple Harris, Sacramento, Calif.\nCOLDER WEATHER\nCHECKING FLOOD\nTHREATS IN PNW\nSEATTLE, Feb. 18.\u2014UR\u2014 Parts\nof the Pacific Northwest still are\nthreatened by floods, although cold\ner weather has checked the threat\nin some regions.\nInland areas of the northwest are\nhaving colder weather, which is\nputting a brake on swollen streams.\nCold air is spreading into the\nnorthern plains, and a new snow\nj fall is harassing Wyoming.\nThe frigate bird, clocked at 261\nmiles an hour, is the fastest feath\nered flyer.\nI\nATLANTIC\nALLIANCE\nSTUDIED\nCommittee Is Puzzled Re\ngarding Stand in Case\nMember Attacked\n(By The Associated Press)\nThe Senate Foreign Relations\nCommittee puzzled today over how\nfar the United States should com\nmit itself under the proposed At\nlantic defense treaty.\nThe committee called in Secre\ntary of State Dean Acheson tor a\nstudy cf just how to word the pro- j\nposed alliance.\nThus far unsettled is the wording\nof a defense clause\u2014the problem\nof what to promise if one of the\nmember states of the security sys\ntem is attacked.\nPiesident Truman reaffirmed at a\nnews conference yesterday that\nAmerican policy calls for the agree\nment to provide: \u201cUnmistakable\nproof of the joint determination\nof the free countries to resist arm\ned attack from any quarter.\u201d\nThe treaty proposal is expected to\nbe submitted at once to other na\ntions in on the negotiations, ij\nthe Senate Committee approves the\nwording of the pact. The coun\ntries include Canada and five west\nern Eurcp^n countries Great\nBritain, France, Belgium, The Neth\nI erlands and Luxembourg.\nSome of the other European na\nI tions are openly worried as to just\nj how far the United States intends\nto go under the alliance.\nNorway\u2019s Labor party newspaper\nasserted today Norway must adhere\nto the Atlantic Pact, instead of \u201can\ni isolated neutrality which we cannot\nj delend.\u201d\nLIMIT ON FISH\ni IMPORTS ASKED\nFROM CONGRESS\ni\ni\nWASHINGTON, Feb. 18.\u2014<#)\u2014\nEast and West Coast fishery spokes\nmen have joined In asking Congress\nto limit fish imports.\nThey told a House Fisheries Sub\nccmmitttee that current tariff bar- i\nriers otter little or no protection\nand that the domestic industry is\nunable to meet foreign competition.\nThe committee has been studying\nfishing industry problems with a\nview to drafting remedial legisla\ntion.\nWitnesses from Hew England pro\nposed that an annual import quota\nof 43,000,000 pounds be imposed,\nsaying fliat import duties would\nhave to be raised to \u201cfantastic\".\nheights before they could afford ef\nfective protection.\nJoseph A. White, business agent\nof the Gloucester, Mass., Seafood\nWorkers\u2019 Union (AFL) said that\neven a 100 per cent boost of tariff\nrates would not solve the problem.\nWest Coast spokesman said they\nare threatened by imports of can\nned qnd fresh v tuna from South\nAmerica and Japan.\nABOARD PNA FLIGHTS\nIN AND OUT THURSDAY\nPassengers aboard Pacific North\nern Airlines flights yesterday in\ncluded the following:\nFrom Anchorage: Major Prank\nGriffin, M. D. Huffaker, J. Frobose,\nNorman Haley.\nFrom Cordova: A. L. Kaye.\nTo Gustavus: Mrs. Archie Chase,\nLyle Bieber.\nTo Anchorage: A. Jones, Glen\nWildei, Walter Walsh, J. S. Rude.\nTo Kodiak: Mr. and Mrs. Vic.\nShenitzler and Vickie.\nARMY PLANE CRASH;\n8 BELIEVED KILLED\ni\nI BUENOS AIRES, Feb. 18.\u2014Ufi\u2014\nI The American Embassy said today\nj that eight persons are believed to\ni have perished in the crash of a\n|U. S. Army C-47 plane near Salta,\ni Argentina, south of the Bolivian\nj border.\nIN FROM SKAGWAY\nRegistered at the Oastineau from\nStagway is Howard Welch.\nTRUMAN NOT\nWORRIED BY\nDOWNTREND\nCurrent Price Drops Only\nHealthy Leveling-Off,\nSays President\nBy FRANCIS M. LE MAY\nWASHINGTON, Feb. 18.\u2014(APT\u2014\nPresident Truman's confident fore\ncast of continued prosperity brought\nthis reaction today from his Capi\ntol Hill critics: The best way to help\nthe nation\u2019s business is to leave it\nalone\nThe President also renewed his re\nquest yesterday for a $4,000,000,000\ntax boost\u2014a proposal which appear\ned to be picking up support from\nDemocrats, but only if necessary to\nkeep the treasury out of the red.\nThere is a lot of opposition, how\never.\nMr. Truman told his Thursday\nnews conference current price drops\nare only the leveling-off that every\nbody has been hoping for, and he\nspoke confidently of the business\noutlook. He. said the business situa\ntion is nothing to be alarmed about.\nSome critics agreed that the lev\nelling off is healthy. But they said\nthe President\u2019s economic control\nprogram, if approved by Congress,\nmight turn a healthy recession into\na depression.\nOTHER DEVELOPMENTS\nWhile Mr. Truman took the eco\nnomic temperature, there were these\nother developments:\n1. Buying interest in the New\nYork Stock Market sharpened yes\nterday and the market moved ahead\nfor the best overall advance in si\nweeks.\n2. At Cleveland, the Chesapeake\nOhio Railroad announced tem\nporary layoffs for more than 4,000\nemployees in four areas. A spokes\nman blamed declining passenger\nbusiness and slower movement of\ncoal due to a mild winter.\nFIVE DAY FURLOUGH\n3. The Baltimore Ohio Rail\nroad, ordered a five-day furlough late\nthis month of 2.521 of its shop em\nployees.\n4. A majority of the 17-private\nindustry economists attending a\nCapitol Hill conference spoke out\nagainst the Administration\u2019s re\nquest for higher taxes and wage\nprice allocation controls.\nThe House yesterday voted to let\nthe President keep part of the power\nhe now has. A bill extending export\ncontrols for 28 months was passed\nand sent to the Senate, which has\napproved a similar measure with\nslight differences\nMr. Truman told his news con\nference, in answer to a question,\nthat he has no plan now to modify\ninstallment buying controls. \u00abRep.\nPatman (D-Tex) has argued the\ncontrols are hurting business.\nALASKA STEAM\nPROPOSES NEW\nCHARTER DEAL\nSEATTLE, Feb. 18.\u2014(/PI\u2014G. W\nSkinner, President of Alaska Steam\nship Company, confirmed reports\ntoday that his company has sub\nmitted a new charter arrangement\nproposal to the maritime commis\nsion for the Alaska trade.\nSkinner said the plan is designed\nto provide sufficient vessels for the\ntrade during the peak shipping sea\nj son in spring and summer months.\nA commission decision on the re\nquest is expected next week, accord\ning to word from Washington, D. C.\nThe company asked authority tc\nmaintain surplus ships on a year\naround basis, paying charter costs\nonly when vessels are in use and\npaying maintenance costs when\nships are idle.\nSkinner said this would not re\nduce company costs, but would as\nsure the trade of having enough\nships to meet shipping needs. It\nalso would save the government ex\npense of taking ships in and out\nof layup, he added.\n\"We regard it as a step in the\nright direction,\u2019\u2019 Skinner concluded\n\"although it definitely is not the\ncomplete answer to all our prob\nlems.\u2019\u2019\nFROM FAIRBANKS\nLeo Kaye of Fairbanks Is\ntend at the Baranof Hotel.\nregis\nCars Flee Flood\nMany cars were trapped on Oregon roads its sudden thaw fltod'.d mast of the State. Here two splash\ntoward safety as fast-rising ereek washed over wide area near Portland. IP) Wirephoto.\nU Michigan Junior Is\nTo Try to Oufeat Hog\nI\nPIONEERS' HOME\nBILL GETS ROUGH\nHOUSE HANDLING\nA House bill for a Pioneer wom\nen's home or homes ran into as\nmuch trouble in the House this\nmorning as a sidetracked sister\nmeasure had encountered previously\nin the Senate.\nAfter almost an hour's argument\nthis morning, the mangled bill ap\npeared headed back for redrafting\nin committee. The move to re-refer\nwas interrupted by the noon recess.\nThe measure was introduced by\nthe three feminine house members\u2014\nEssie Dale, Amelia Gundersen and\nDoris Barnes.\nAbout the only specific action the\nHouse took on the bill was to elimi\nnate the proposal for a home at\nFairbanks as well as at Sitka 01\nWrangell.\nMrs. Dale moved to eliminate the\nFairbanks proposal because she had\nfound no need there. She said old\nfolks told her they would rather\ngo to Sitka, where the Pioneer\nmen's home is located.\nWith the elimination of the Fair\nbanks project, the women sponsors\nalso offered an amertdment to cut\nthe appropriation from $200,000 to\n$100,000. The $200,000 item already\nhad been cleared ty the House Ways\nand Means committee.\nTwo motions were before the\nHouse at recess time. Jack Conrighi\nmoved to send the bill back to com\nmittee for redrafting. Warren Tay\nlor had moved to strike the whole\nsection providing for the Pioneer\nWomen\u2019s building at Sitka or Wran\ngell. He said it should be left to the\ndecision of the commission which\nwould be established under the bill.\nA similar bill for a Pioneer Wom\nen\u2019s Home building or annex at\nSitka has been postponed until the\nend of the month in the Senate, af\nter having reached the floor there\ntwice. Senator Anita Garnick is its\nauthor.\nSTOCK QUOTATIONS\nNEW YORK. Feb. 18.\u2014(jW\u2014Clos\ning quotation of Alaska Juneau\nmine stock today is 3 American\nCon 88. Anaconda 32>4, Curtiss\nWright 9'}., International Harvest\ner 24%, Kennecott 48%. New York\nCentral 11%, Northern Pacific 14%,\nU S. Steel 71%, Pound $4.03%.\nSales today were 650,000 shares.\nAverages today are as follows:\nindustrials 174.71, rails 49.21; util\nities 34.60.\nSTE AMElfMOVEMENTS\nPrincess Norah from Vancouver\nscheduled to arrive Sunday after\nnoon or evening.\nBaranof scheduled to sail from\nSeattle tomorrow.\nAlaska from west scheduled\nsouthbound Monday.\nANN ARBOR, Mich., Peb. 18.\u2014(^1\n\u2014A University of Michigan junior\nsaid today that he would try to out\neat a hog.\nThe contest is scheduled for Sat\nurday between Paul H. Smith, an\nengineering student, and Broadview\nPerfect Lad, a four-months-old hog.\nBoth will weigh in as welcef\nweights\u2014at 165 pounds. Smith hopes]\nto match pound for pound of food\nwith the hog until the animal calls\nt quits.\nThe contest climaxed a growing\nseries ol gastronomical feats on the\ncampus. One student ate 48 oysters\nand a second bfsted him ty eating\n70. A girl student ate 12*i ham\nburgers, falling half a burger short\nof the intercollegiate record.\nDr. Warren E. Forsythe of the\nUniversity Health Service, called the\nexhibitions \u2018disgusting and silly\u201d\nand remarked:\n\"You could go and get a hog that\ncould eat more than that.\u201d\nSmith said he would try to prove\nDr. Forsythe wrong.\nBODY OF AMERICAN\nIS FOUND IN RAVINE\nNEAR WRECK SCENE\nATHENS, Feb. 18.\u2014OB\u2014A body j\nfound in a ravine near Karpenisl j\ni has been identified positively as I\n1 that of Lieutenant Colonel Selden j\nEdner, an American Air Force offi- I\nj cer.\nThe Ameiican Mission announced i\nthat the identification had been\nmade from medical records.\nEdner was from San Jose, Calif, j\nHe was 30 yeras old. He was an\nunarmed observer aboard a Greek\nRcyal Airforce plane which made\na forced landing in Karpenfti on\nJanuary 21st.\nThe Greek guerrilla radio said\nsoon after the crash landing that\nEdner had died of injuries suffer\ned in the crash.\nA Greek Army colonel said af\ntei an investigation that it was\nsafe to- conclude that Edner was\nkilled within two hours after the\nplane landed. The colonel said vil-\nlagers told him they saw many!\nguerrillas running toward the spot\nimmediately after the crash.\nTRUMAN'S AIMS\ni By The Associated Press)\nPresident Truman told the news\nmen chat he stands on what he\nsaid belore:\nHe still wants taxes increased by j\nfour billion dollars\nHe still takes a confident view j\nof the business oatlook\nAnd he means what he previously\nsaid about the objectives of the pro\nposed North Atlantic Defense Al\nliance\ni Furthermore, the President told\nh!\" news conference\u2014there's been j\nno change whatever in American\npolicy regarding the occupation of j\nJapan.\nSNOW SMUDGE IS\nCAUSE, SNOWSLIDE\nFor over one minute this forenoon,\nJuneau was caught in a regular\nsnow smudge. A snowslide on Mount\nJuneau occurred and came roaring\ndown spraying snow over the city,\nacross the channel almost to Doug\nlas.\nThe slide came down from Mount\nI Juneau and struck halfway between\nI the wooden bridge and the trestle on\nthe Basin road. The slide, 20 feet\nwide, came across Gold Creek, and\nup' the side, piling 15 feet deep on\nthe Basin road, according to H. A.\nStoddart, Division Engineer of the\nPublic Roads Administration.\nThe Basin road will be eleared\nby Sunday, permitting traffic..\nTwo employees of the Juneau\nWater Company consider they had\na narrow escape.\nPete Petrovich and E. H. Kirchoier\nwere working in the creek bottom,\nchecking the penstock of Gold Creek.\nThey heard the slide, and ran for\ntheir lives.\nTheir truck, at first believed to\nbe caught in the slide, was missed,\nand still is on the farther side ol\nthe slide.\nCONFIRMED\nWASHINGTON, Feb. 18.\u2014W- The\nSenate has confirmed the nomina\ntions of these United States attor\nneys:\nFrank C. Bingham for Division\nNo. 2 of the District of Alaska.\nHarry O. Arend for Division No.\n14, Alaska.\nThey have been serving under\nj previous appointments.\nGERMAN POLICE\nKILL GERMAN IN\nBLOCKADE CONTROL\nBy THOMAS A. REEDY\nBERLIN, Feb. 18- -W\u2014Soviet-con\ntrolled German police killed another\nGerman while tightening their\nblockadfe, and the incident heighten\ned tension today between Commun\nists and their foes who charged the\nshooting was \"murder.\"\nSporadic fist fights were report\ned on subwtty and elevated trains\nbetween German passengers and\nQonununist-controlled police, who\nsought to search and seize their be\nlongings.\ni A German man and a 14-year-old\ngirl, Innocent bystanders, were\nj wounded in another sector border\nj incident.\nj 'COUNCIL melts tonight\ni Matters to come before the Ju\nj neau City Council at tonight's regu\nj lar meeting will be chiefly of a\nroutine nature, according to May\nor Waino Hendrickson.\nDefinitely on the agenda are\nthird and final reading of Ordin\nj ance No. 326, to negotiate $260,000\nI of paving bonds: establishment of\nprecincts for the next municipal\ni election, and payment of bills.\nI\nTEN MILL\nTAX LEVY\nOp 12-4\nMeasure Now Goes Back\nto House for Approval\nof Amendments\nBULLETIN\u2014The Home this\naftemcon concurred in toto to\nall Senate amendments and the\nmeasure now goes to the Gov\nernor fer his signature.\nBy BOB DeARMOND\nThe General Property Tax Bill\ncame unexpectedly to the Senate\nfloor this morning under a suspen\nsion of the rules and quickly passed\nby a 12-4 vote. There was almost no\npreliminary fuss or flurry.\nThe only votes cast against the\nLill were by Senators Dawes and\nj Garnlck of the First Division and\nSenators Jones and Munz of the\nsecond.\nSenators Butrovich and Rivers\nsupported the measure in the short\ndebate preceding passage; Senator\nJones spoke against it.\nI The bill now goes back to the\nHouse, where it originated, for the\nHouse to approve or disapprove the\namendments adopted by the Senate.\nThe amendment most Ukely to\nmeet with the House opposition is\nthe one reducing personal property\nexemptions from 12500 to $200.\nIf the House approves the amend\njments made by the Senate the bUl\nI will go to the governor for approval;\nif the House does not approve the\nSenate amendments, the bill will go\nto a Conference Committee of six\nmembers, three from each the House\nand Senate.*\nHARD ON MINERS\nThe Property Tax BUI came back\nfrom the Engrossment Committee\nthis morning and Senator McCutch\neon immediately moved for third\nreading and final passage. There\nwas no objection.\nSenator Charles D. Jones took the\nfloor with the announcement that\nsince the amendment he had of\nfered to aid the \"very sick\u201d mining\nindustry had received only four\nvotes, he would be unable to support\nthe oill.\nRetouching a picture he had pre\nviously painted of the difficulties\nof profitable mining, Senator Jones\nsaid that many of the small mining\noperators in the Second Division will\nclose down next season.\n\"With the severe restrictions\nplaced on the sale of gold, the gov\nernment holding it at $35 an ounce\nwhile the world price is around $72,\nthe miners are unable to assume\nany additional costs,\u201d Senator Jones\nasserted.\nA PAIR TAX\n\"This is as lair a means of rais\ning revenues to operate the Terri\ntory as any we qould pass,\" Sena\ntor Butrovich told his colleagues.\nHe admitted that it is not pain\nless but felt that one of its greatest\nmerits is that it is not aimed at\nany one industry or class of taxpay\ners.\nThe amount of revenues the tax\nwould bring in was the only reason\nfor any qualms concerning it, the\nsenator said.\n\u2018\u2018I voted against this bill in the\n1947 session because I doubted then\nthat it would bring enough reve\nnues to offset the costs and diffi\nculties of assessing and collecting\nthe tax,\u201d Senator Butrovich said.\n\u25a0Our experience in collecting taxes\nin independent school districts has\nproved that I was wrong,\u201d he added.\nINCOME AND WEALTH\nFair and equitable taxes include\nthose on income and wealth, both of\nwhich are based upon ability to pay,\nthe senator explained.\n\"We have already passed a till to\ntax income and if there is any\nwish among the members ot this\nbody to enact equitable tax legisla\ntion, this bill should get 16 votes\nhere.\u201d Senator Butrovich concluded.\nSenator Victor Rivers asserted\nthat the Territorial treasury is in\nthe worst condition ever although\nAlaska has had the biggest boom\nin its history.\nHe pointed to the failure of past\nlegislatures to pass basic tax laws\nas the cause of this condition.\nWe have always gone home from\npast sessions after having provided\nonly for the barest necessities,\u201d\nSenator Rivers said and expressed\nthe hope that the \u201cgreat need for\nschools, hospitals and other facili\nties for the welfare of our people\ncan be taken care of.\u201d _\n(Continued on Page Five)","height":"26420","width":"21148"}}
